// Experiment Culture Decision Tree for SAP Engineers
// Use this to reframe any technical decision as an experiment

[?] Can you measure the outcome quantitatively?
    |
    Yes --> [?] Can you isolate the change from other variables?
    |           |
    |           Yes --> Run a controlled experiment (A/B test)
    |           No  --> Use a cohort analysis or pre/post comparison
    |
    No --> [?] Is the change irreversible or high-cost?
              |
              Yes --> Use a phased rollout with monitoring
              No  --> Make the decision qualitatively, then measure

// FAANG rule: If you cannot measure it, you cannot optimize it.
// SAP rule: If you can spec it, you can build it.
// These are different philosophies. FAANG wins.

// Staff+ minimum: Every major technical decision must include:
// 1. How you will measure success
// 2. What the counterfactual is (what would happen if you did nothing)
// 3. How long before you know if the decision was right

// Experiment Design Cheat Sheet for Staff+ Engineers

// 1. PRE-REGISTER YOUR METRICS
// Before the experiment starts, document:
//   - Primary metric (the one you'll bet the launch decision on)
//   - Secondary metrics (supporting context, no launch authority)
//   - Guardrail metrics (must not degrade — can veto launch)

// 2. COMPUTE SAMPLE SIZE
//   n = (Z_alpha/2 + Z_beta)^2 * 2 * sigma^2 / delta^2
//   Where:
//     Z_alpha/2 = 1.96 (for 95% confidence)
//     Z_beta = 0.84 (for 80% power)
//     sigma = standard deviation of the metric
//     delta = minimum detectable effect
//
//   If you need 10M users and only have 1M, your experiment is
//   underpowered. Don't run it — you'll make wrong decisions.

// 3. RUN DURATION
//   Minimum: 1 full business cycle (1 week for most products)
//   Longer for: novelty effects, weekly seasonality, low-traffic
//   Never: stop early just because results look significant

// 4. LAUNCH DECISION MATRIX
//   Primary positive + All guardrails green = Launch
//   Primary positive + Any guardrail red = Investigate, don't launch
//   Primary flat + Secondary positive = Iterate, don't launch
//   Primary negative = Kill or investigate further
//   Primary flat + All flat = The change doesn't matter. Ship it or kill it.

// From Process Culture to Data Culture — Mindset Shift
// SAP: "Did we follow the blueprint?"
// FAANG: "Did we learn something?"

// Old mindset (process-driven):
[ ] All requirements documented
[ ] Design reviewed and approved
[ ] Test cases 100% coverage
[ ] Transport approved by change board

// New mindset (data-driven):
[ ] Hypothesis defined
[ ] Success metric chosen
[ ] Experiment designed before implementation
[ ] Measurement pipeline built before feature ships
[ ] Pre-registered — no cherry-picking metrics after
[ ] Go/no-go criteria defined upfront

// SAP engineers tend to over-engineer the process
// and under-invest in the measurement.
// FAANG does the opposite.

// Practical rule: Before writing any code,
// write the experiment design first.
// The experiment design IS the requirements document.
